Forecasting Physical Activity Across a Decade: A Machine Learning Exploration of Affect and Biopsychosocial Predictors

Final Project
Data Science 2 with R (STAT 301-2)

Angela Zhong

Introduction

This project seeks to address a critical public health and clinical psychology question: how psychological states and baseline behaviors influence long-term physical activity patterns. By identifying predictors of sustained physical activity, the findings could inform interventions to promote healthier lifestyles. Additionally, this project contributes to a broader research effort that Iâm working on, which focuses on exploring bidirectional relationships between physical activity and positive/negative affect over time.

Data source

The data for this project comes from the Midlife in the United States (MIDUS) study, a longitudinal investigation of health and well-being in U.S. adults. The study began in 1995 (Time 1) and includes follow-ups at approximately 9-year intervals. This analysis uses the MIDUS Core sample from Time 2 (2004â2006) and Time 3 (2013â2014), which spans a 9-year observational period.

The MIDUS dataset is publicly accessible for research purposes1, with ethical approval and detailed methodology described in prior publications. The longitudinal design and inclusion of biopsychosocial variables make it well-suited for investigating predictors of long-term health behaviors.

1Â MIDUS data documentation and access

Core Sample Overview

  • Time 2 (2004â2006): The Core sample included 4,963 participants (M = 55 years, SD = 12.4; 53% female; 90.1% White).
    • Physical activity: 77.51% of the Core sample (n = 4,963).
  • Time 3 (2013â2014): The Core sample retained 2,902 participants (M = 63.94 years, SD = 11.35; 55.9% female; 89.5% White), reflecting attrition over the 9-year interval.
    • Physical activity: 88.01% of the retained Core sample (n = 2,902).

Target variable analysis

The total physical activity score at Time 3 is calculated by combining measurements across three intensity levels (light, moderate, vigorous), three activity types (job, chores, leisure), and two seasons (summer, winter). Participants reported their physical activity on a scale of 1 (several times a week) to 6 (never), with a higher score indicating fewer, less frequent physical activity. For each intensity-activity combination, the summer and winter scores are averaged with missing value handling. These averages are then combined to create subtotals for each intensity level (vigorous_total, moderate_total, light_total) by averaging across activity types. Finally, the total physical activity score is computed as the mean of these three intensity subtotals, providing a comprehensive measure of overall physical activity that accounts for all dimensions of the data.

Physical Activity by Intensity and Season

Examining the subscores through FigureÂ 1 reveals several patterns. Activity levels consistently differ across intensities, with vigorous activities showing the highest median scores (indicating less frequent activity), followed by moderate activities, and then light activities showing the lowest median scores (indicating more frequent activity). This pattern is intuitive as lighter activities tend to be more frequent in daily life. There are also seasonal variations, with lower median scores (indicating more frequent activity) in summer compared to winter for vigorous activities.

Total Physical Activity Score

As shown in FigureÂ 2, the total physical activity score distribution appears to be approximately normal, centered around a mean of 3.5 (red dashed line) which almost overlaps with the median (grey dashed line) - a characteristic of normal distributions. The histogram with density overlay shows a roughly bell-shaped pattern, with scores most concentrated in the middle range (3-4) and gradually decreasing frequencies toward both extremes. While there appears to be slightly more spread toward higher values (5-6, indicating less frequent activity) than lower values (1-2, indicating more frequent activity), this deviation from perfect normality is minor. Notably, the distribution shows a higher frequency of extreme low values (score of 1, indicating very frequent activity) compared to extreme high values (score of 6, indicating very infrequent activity). The roughly normal distribution suggests that most participants report moderate frequency of physical activity, with progressively fewer people reporting either very frequent or very infrequent physical activity - a pattern that is quite common in behavioral measures.

Methods

Prediction Problem

The primary objective of this prediction task is to predict physical activity levels at Time 3 (2013â2014) using longitudinal predictors measured at Time 2 (2004â2006). Predictors include baseline physical activity, psychological factors (positive and negative affect subdivided into high- and low-arousal categories), demographic variables (age, sex, race), health-related indicators (BMI, chronic conditions, self-rated health), socioeconomic status (education, income), and psychological/lifestyle factors (perceived stress, social support, smoking, and alcohol use). This is a regression problem, as the outcome variableâtotal physical activity scoreâis continuous.

Predictors

  • Baseline physical activity at Time 2
    • Total physical activity scoreâaveraged across light, moderate, vigorous for summer/winter
  • Affect at Time 2(based on PANAS, NAPAS; break down into 4 arousal-based predictors)
    • High-arousal positive affect (e.g., PANAS: âenthusiastic,â âactiveâ)
    • Low-arousal positive affect (e.g., NAPAS: âcalm,â âsatisfiedâ)
    • High-arousal negative affect (e.g., PANAS: âjittery,â âupsetâ)
    • Low-arousal negative affect (e.g., NAPAS: âhopeless,â âlonelyâ)
  • Demographics
    • Age (continuous)
    • Sex (binary: male/female)
  • Health Status
    • BMI: Body Mass Index
    • Self-rated physical health
    • Self-rated health compared to others the same age
  • Socioeconomic Status
    • Education level
    • Household income
  • Psychological Factors
    • Self-evaluated mental health
    • Life satisfaction
    • Perceived stress (aggregated from PSS scale)

Data Splitting

Training/Testing Split: 75% training, 25% testing. Stratified sampling will ensure proportional representation of sex across splits.

Resampling: 5-fold cross-validation on the training set to tune hyperparameters and evaluate performance. Cross-validation is preferred over bootstrap due to computational efficiency and the moderate sample size.

Model Types & Tuning paramaters

Null Model

The null model serves as a baseline for comparison, predicting the mean physical activity score for all observations regardless of input features. This model provides a benchmark RMSE, representing the error if no predictors were used. No tuning is required for this model.

Ordinary Linear Regression

Ordinary linear regression models the relationship between predictors and the outcome as a linear combination of input features. It assumes additivity and linearity, making it a simple yet interpretable baseline. However, it may struggle with complex, non-linear relationships in the data. No tuning is required for this model.

Elastic Net

Elastic Net combines L1 (lasso) and L2 (ridge) regularization to handle multicollinearity and perform feature selection. It is particularly useful for datasets with correlated predictors, such as the affect subscales in MIDUS. The following parameters are tuned:

  • Penalty (Î»): Controls the overall strength of regularization.

  • Mixture (Î±): Balances L1 and L2 penalties (Î± = 1 for lasso, Î± = 0 for ridge).

Random Forest

Random Forest is an ensemble method that builds multiple decision trees and aggregates their predictions. It is robust to non-linear relationships and interactions, making it well-suited for biopsychosocial data like MIDUS. The following parameters are tuned:

  • Trees: Number of trees in the ensemble (500â1000).

  • mtry: Number of predictors sampled for each split (2â10).

  • min_n: Minimum number of observations required to split a node (10â40).

Boosted Trees

Boosted Trees iteratively builds decision trees, with each tree correcting errors from the previous one. It is highly flexible and can capture complex patterns in the data. The following parameters are tuned:

  • Trees: Number of boosting iterations (250â1000).

  • Tree Depth: Maximum depth of each tree (3â8).

  • Learn Rate: Step size for each iteration (0.005â0.1).

  • Loss Reduction (Gamma): Minimum loss reduction required to make a split (0â1).

Nearest Neighbors

KNN predicts the outcome by averaging the values of the k nearest neighbors in the feature space. It is a non-parametric method that can capture local patterns but may struggle with high-dimensional data. The following parameter is tuned:

  • Neighbors: Number of neighbors (k) to consider (5â20).

Recipes

Recipe 1 (Basic Preprocessing)

  • Predictors
    • baseline physical activity (Time 2 total score)
    • four affect subscales (high-arousal positive, low-arousal positive, high-arousal negative, low-arousal negative)
    • demographics (age, sex)
    • health status (BMI, self-rated health)
    • socioeconomic factors (education, household income)
  • Steps
    • replace missing numeric predictors (e.g., income, BMI) with their median values.
    • dummy encode categorical variables - convert sex (male/female) into a binary numeric variable (0/1)
    • normalize numeric predictors: scale and center all numeric variables (e.g., age, income) to mean = 0, SD = 1

Recipe 2 (Interaction Terms)

  • Predictors: All predictors in Recipe 1
    • Interactions between baseline physical activity and each affect subscale (e.g., baseline activity Ã high-arousal positive affect)
  • Steps
    • impute missing values - same as Recipe 1
    • dummy encode categorical variable - same as Recipe 1
    • add interaction terms between baseline physical activity and the four affect subscales
    • normalize numeric predictors - same as Recipe 1

Recipe 3 (High Arousal Emotions Only)

  • Predictors
    • baseline physical activity (Time 2 total score)
    • two affect subscales (high-arousal positive, high-arousal negative)
    • demographics (age, sex)
    • health status (BMI, self-rated health)
    • socioeconomic factors (education, household income)
  • Steps
    • replace missing numeric predictors (e.g., income, BMI) with their median values.
    • dummy encode categorical variables - convert sex (male/female) into a binary numeric variable (0/1)
    • normalize numeric predictors: scale and center all numeric variables (e.g., age, income) to mean = 0, SD = 1

Assessment Metrics

The primary metric for evaluating model performance is Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE), which quantifies the average deviation between predicted and observed values of physical activity. Along with Standard Error (SE), RMSE is particularly useful in this context for three reasons: - RMSE retains the original units of the outcome variable, making it easy to compare across models and assess practical significance. - Squaring residuals penalizes larger errors more heavily, ensuring models that consistently make large mistakes are appropriately downweighted. - RMSE enables direct comparison to the null model (which predicts the mean physical activity score) and across different modeling approaches, from simple regressions to tree-based methods.

Final model is assess based on RMSE, RÂ², and MAE.

Model Building & Selection Results

Model Performance Overview

TableÂ 1 summarizes the best-performing versions of each model-recipe combination, sorted by RMSE:

Model Performance Analysis

Null Model
The null model, which predicts the mean physical activity score for all observations, achieved an RMSE of 1.221 (SE = 0.009). This baseline serves as the critical threshold for evaluating model effectiveness. Any model failing to improve upon this value is considered ineffective.

Linear Regression
Linear regression outperformed all other models across all recipes, with RMSE values between 1.043â1.046. The High recipe achieved the lowest RMSE (1.043), suggesting that high-arousal affect variables (e.g., âenthusiastic,â âjitteryâ) have a linear relationship with physical activity. This contrasts with expectations, as tree-based models typically dominate in biopsychosocial datasets.

Elastic Net
Regularized regression underperformed compared to linear regression, with the best RMSE (1.056) in the Interact recipe. The optimal hyperparameters (Î» = 1, Î± = 0) reduced the model to ridge regression, but this did not improve performance over simpler linear models. The lack of improvement suggests that multicollinearity was not a major issue or that regularization oversimplified the model.

Random Forest
Random Forest achieved moderate performance, with the High recipe yielding the best RMSE (1.054). The optimal hyperparameters (trees = 437, mtry = 2, min_n = 50) indicate shallow trees with limited variable sampling, which may have restricted the modelâs ability to capture complex patterns.

Boosted Tree Boosted Trees performed poorly (RMSE: 1.078â1.090), likely due to suboptimal hyperparameters: excessively high learn_rate = 1.012 (typical range: 0.01â0.3) and shallow tree_depth = 2â3, limiting non-linear feature interactions.

K-Nearest Neighbors
KNN had the worst performance (RMSE: 1.127â1.146), indicating that local similarity patterns in the feature space provide little predictive signal for physical activity.

Comparison between Recipes

Interact Recipe: Improved Elastic Net performance marginally (ÎRMSE = -0.015 vs.Â Basic recipe). Had negligible impact on other models, suggesting interaction terms were either redundant or already captured by tree-based methods.

High Recipe: Reduced RMSE by 0.1% for Random Forest and 0.4% for Linear Regression compared to the Basic recipe.Highlighted the role of high-arousal emotions (e.g., âenthusiasticâ) as predictors, though the effect was modest. Psychological theory generally supports this finding, as high-arousal statesâregardless of emotional valenceâ(e.g., enthusiasm) are more likely to motivate physical activity than low-arousal states.

Basic Recipe: Underperformed relative to specialized recipes, underscoring the necessity of feature engineering.

Final Model Selection

The Linear Regression with the High recipe (RMSE = 1.043) was selected as the final model. This decision is justified by:

  1. Performance: It achieved the lowest RMSE across all models, reducing prediction error by 14.6% compared to the null model (ÎRMSE = 0.178).

  2. Simplicity: Linear regressionâs outperformance of tree-based models suggests the relationships between predictors and physical activity are predominantly linear.

  3. Theoretical Alignment: The High recipeâs focus on high-arousal affect matches established psychological frameworks linking energetic states to health behaviors.

The superiority of linear regression over more complex models was surprising. Linear regression, with the High recipe, achieved the lowest RMSE (1.043), outperforming tree-based models by a significant margin. This challenges the common assumption that biopsychosocial data, with its inherent complexity and potential for non-linear relationships, requires sophisticated machine learning methods. Instead, the results suggest that the relationships between predictors (e.g., high-arousal affect, baseline physical activity) and the outcome (physical activity at Time 3) are predominantly linear. This finding has important implications for future research, as it highlights the value of starting with simple, interpretable models before resorting to more complex approaches.

In addition, the Random Forest model did not achieve the expected dominance over linear regression. Its best RMSE (1.054) was only marginally better than Elastic Net and significantly worse than linear regression. This may reflect overly conservative hyperparameters (e.g., mtry = 2, min_n = 50), which limited the modelâs ability to capture complex patterns. However, re-tuning with broader ranges (e.g., mtry = 4â14, min_n = 10â20) did not improve performance, indicating that the issue may lie in the dataset itself rather than the model configuration.

Final Model Analysis

The final model, linear regression with high-arousal emotions only, was selected as the best-performing model based on its performance metrics on the test set. The root mean squared error (RMSE) was 1.0631, indicating the average prediction error in the same units as the total physical activity score. The model explained approximately 23.15% of the variance in the outcome variable (RÂ² = 0.2315), suggesting a moderate predictive capability. The mean absolute error (MAE) was 0.8415, providing an additional measure of prediction accuracy that is less sensitive to extreme errors compared to RMSE.

To further assess the modelâs performance, a scatterplot comparing predicted vs.Â actual physical activity scores (FigureÂ 3) was generated. While there is a general positive correlation along the y = x line, the spread of points suggests variability in the modelâs predictive accuracy. Some underestimation and overestimation patterns are noticeable, particularly at higher values of physical activity scores.

While the linear regression with high-arousal emotions only model outperformed alternative models, its explanatory power is limited. The modest RÂ² value suggests that other unmodeled factors influence physical activity scores. Future work could explore additional predictors, interaction terms, or non-linear modeling techniques to enhance predictive accuracy.

Conclusion

This study leveraged longitudinal data from the Midlife in the United States (MIDUS) cohort to predict physical activity patterns over a 9-year period (2004â2014) using biopsychosocial predictors measured at baseline. Focusing on 2,902 participants with complete data, the analysis tested six machine learning models across three feature-engineered recipes to evaluate the predictive power of high- and low-arousal emotions, demographics, health metrics, and socioeconomic factors. The simplicity of linear regression unexpectedly outperformed complex models like Random Forest, with the High-arousal recipe (prioritizing energetic emotional states) emerging as the most effective.

The superiority of a simple linear regression model over more complex methods like Random Forest challenges assumptions about the necessity of non-linear modeling for biopsychosocial data, suggesting that linear relationships dominate in this context. The final modelâs moderate performance (RÂ² = 0.232) underscores the multifactorial nature of physical activity, with factors beyond affectâsuch as environmental, genetic, or unmeasured behavioral variablesâlikely playing significant roles.

While the modelâs performance is modest, its interpretability and alignment with psychological theory make it a valuable tool for generating hypotheses and guiding future research. The findings reinforce the importance of emotional states in health behavior and highlight the need for holistic approaches to physical activity promotion.It also provides actionable insights for public health interventions. For example, programs targeting emotional regulation or enthusiasm-building could indirectly promote physical activity.

Future Directions

  • Expand Predictors: Incorporate additional variables (e.g., social support, neighborhood walkability) to improve explanatory power.

  • Non-Linear Exploration: Test spline terms or interaction effects within the linear framework to capture subtle non-linearities.

  • Longitudinal Analysis: Model changes in affect and physical activity over time using mixed-effects or growth curve models.

  • Intervention Design: Use the identified high-arousal affect predictors to pilot targeted behavioral interventions (e.g., enthusiasm-boosting programs).
